    <item>
      <title>optimization</title>
      <link>http://192.168.2.102:1313/posts/optimization/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 01 Mar 2026 15:25:55 +0800</pubDate>
      <guid>http://192.168.2.102:1313/posts/optimization/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&#34;测试图片&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; src=&#34;http://192.168.2.102:1313/images/test.png&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h1 id=&#34;abstract&#34;&gt;Abstract&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Porous cellulose acetate membranes fabricated via solvent-template evaporation-induced phase separation (EIPS) are promising for passive radiative cooling due to their high solar reflectance. We develop a mechanistic mathematical model to optimize and control the membrane’s light reflection performance, quantified by the pore area ratio in SEM images. The model integrates five sequential process stages – solvent evaporation, nonsolvent and polymer precipitation, Brownian diffusion of nascent droplets, droplet coalescence into larger droplets, and growth of large droplets – each grounded in physical theory. Evaporation kinetics are described by a first-order model incorporating DMF vapor pressure (via the Antoine equation) and a linear humidity suppression term. Phase separation of sulfolane (nonsolvent) and polymer is captured by mass balance constraints using solubility limits. Brownian motion of sulfolane droplets is modeled via the Stokes-Einstein diffusion coefficient, with solution viscosity enhanced by precipitated polymer according to Einstein’s effective viscosity relation. Droplet collision kinetics are formulated for both small-small collisions (creating new large droplets) and small-large collisions (growth of existing large droplets). The final pore area ratio is assumed proportional to the total mass of large droplets formed by the end of evaporation.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>第一篇：博客跑通</title>
